<br>
When you accept the commitment to bring life into the world, you accept the responsibility of raising that life to be strong and healthy, in all ways.<br>
<br>
That doesn't mean spoiling the child or doting on it. It means that your first and foremost responsibility in life is not your self but that child. Everything you do, you do because it contributes to the welfare of your children.<br>
<br>
You have a responsibility to be a role model and to provide for that child. You have the responsibility to educate that child in the matters of life.<br>
<br>
You don't have to spend every waking minute tending to your childs needs, but at no time should a parent put their own desires ahead of the childrens needs. When it comes to the parents needs versus the childrens needs, I believe children come first. But, some of the parents needs coming first are closely enough related to the childs welfare that the parents needs are the childrens needs.<br>
<br>
Parents do need time to goof off. They do need time away from the children. They do need to maintain their careers so they may provide for the children. <br>
<br>
And if you think that parenthood ends when the child turns 18.../sigh. Parenthood ends when the parent dies. Your responsibilities as a parent continue for the rest of your life. <br>
<br>
If you do the first 18 years right, though, the responsibilitys beyond that point will be much fewer and far between, and you will probably even be able to expect your children to care for you when you become feeble. Do the first 18 years wrong though, and that child will either be a burden on you or on society.<br>
<br>
Putting your children first means always being aware of them when they are around you. Considering them when you get out of the car. Considering them when you get into the car. Taking an active role in raising them and no, bringing home a pile of toys is not raising them.<br>
<br>
I hope I misread your points in your post. I really do. <br>
If not, then you made the wrong choice in becoming a parent.<br>
<br>
<br>
