  I think I'm mostly arguing against the mindset and excesses of that philosophy. My child gets her discipline, gets her playtime with daddy, gets attention and food and clothing and I've given up lots of activities as a parent. She is considered the best behaved kid by everyone for 4 years, vexing her parents terribly, who know better. She already has multiple boyfriends at 4 (/boggle), that is boys who come up and hug her and do things for her, as well as a lot of friends in general.<br>
<br>
  Glancing back at your post I think the question is over needs vs. wants. I can't remember the pyramid of needs from psychology, but I'm arguing that at some point on that pyramid below self actualization, the parent can say &quot;enough&quot;. <br>
<br>
