Why is a child's life worth more than an adults?  It is a cultural and biological result.  It is not based on an intellectual level.  It is also recent historically.  <br>
<br>
In the 17 and 18th centuries, the odds a woman died in childbirth was 1 in 8 over her lifetime.  10 to 30% of children died before their 5th birthday.  (Based on how healthy the population was.)  A quote from a web page on history from <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://historymedren.about.com/library/weekly/aa112200c.htm">historymedren.about.com/library/weekly/aa112200c.htm</a><!--EZCODE LINK END-->:<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Peasant mothers who had their hands full with myriad daily chores were sometimes unable to keep a constant watch on their offspring, and it was not unknown for them to leave their infants or toddlers unattended. Court records illustrate that this practice was not very common and met with disapproval in the community at large, but negligence was not a crime with which distraught parents were charged when they had lost a child.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
